H11   Spermatogenesis

Spermatogonia develop prenatally. These diploid stem cells occupy the basal compartment. They are thus exposed to the immune system, which considers them “self”. 
At puberty, under the influence of FSH, spermatogonia undergo mitoses to produce more stem cells and also type A spermatogonia, progenitor cells committed to giving rise to mature spermatozoa.
Picture 2
Rectangle 3

Type A spermatogonia undergo mitoses, ultimately giving rise to type B spermatogonia.
With a final mitotic division, type B spermatogonia produce primary (1°) spermatocytes. 
1° spermatocytes migrate from the basal to the adluminal compartment by temporarily disassembling the TJs between adjacent sustentacular cells. The remaining steps in spermatogenesis gives rise to distinct cells that are foreign to the immune system. The basal to adluminal transmigration of 1° spermatocytes shields these cells from immune detection.
1° spermatocytes undergo two rounds of meiosis to give rise to 2° spermatocytes, and then spermatids. Spermatids are the haploid male gametes that are the product of spermatogenesis.
Spermatids next undergo spermiogenesis, a process of differentiation without division that gives rise to functionally mature spermatozoa.
